VI'd like to begin with a thought experiment.
p4
aVImagine that it's 4,000 years into the future.
p5
aVCivilization as we know it
p6
aVhas ceased to exist \u2014
p7
aVno books,
p8
aVno electronic devices,
p9
aVno Facebook or Twitter.
p10
aVAll knowledge of the English language and the English alphabet
p11
aVhas been lost.
p12
aVNow imagine archeologists
p13
aVdigging through the rubble of one of our cities.
p14
aVWhat might they find?
p15
aVWell perhaps some rectangular pieces of plastic
p16
aVwith strange symbols on them.
p17
aVPerhaps some circular pieces of metal.
p18
aVMaybe some cylindrical containers
p19
aVwith some symbols on them.
p20
aVAnd perhaps one archeologist becomes an instant celebrity
p21
aVwhen she discovers \u2014
p22
aVburied in the hills somewhere in North America \u2014
p23
aVmassive versions of these same symbols.
p24
aVNow let's ask ourselves,
p25
aVwhat could such artifacts say about us
p26
aVto people 4,000 years into the future?
p27
aa(lp28
VThis is no hypothetical question.
p29
aVIn fact, this is exactly the kind of question we're faced with
p30
aVwhen we try to understand the Indus Valley civilization,
p31
aVwhich existed 4,000 years ago.
p32
aVThe Indus civilization was roughly contemporaneous
p33
aVwith the much better known Egyptian and the Mesopotamian civilizations,
p34
aVbut it was actually much larger than either of these two civilizations.
p35
aVIt occupied the area
p36
aVof approximately one million square kilometers,
p37
aVcovering what is now Pakistan,
p38
aVNorthwestern India
p39
aVand parts of Afghanistan and Iran.
p40
aVGiven that it was such a vast civilization,
p41
aVyou might expect to find really powerful rulers, kings,
p42
aVand huge monuments glorifying these powerful kings.
p43
aVIn fact,
p44
aVwhat archeologists have found is none of that.
p45
aVThey've found small objects such as these.
p46
aa(lp47
VHere's an example of one of these objects.
p48
aVWell obviously this is a replica.
p49
aVBut who is this person?
p50
aVA king? A god?
p51
aVA priest?
p52
aVOr perhaps an ordinary person
p53
aVlike you or me?
p54
aVWe don't know.
p55
aVBut the Indus people also left behind artifacts with writing on them.
p56
aVWell no, not pieces of plastic,
p57
aVbut stone seals, copper tablets,
p58
aVpottery and, surprisingly,
p59
aVone large sign board,
p60
aVwhich was found buried near the gate of a city.
p61
aVNow we don't know if it says Hollywood,
p62
aVor even Bollywood for that matter.
p63
aVIn fact, we don't even know
p64
aVwhat any of these objects say,
p65
aVand that's because the Indus script is undeciphered.
p66
aVWe don't know what any of these symbols mean.
p67
aa(lp68
VThe symbols are most commonly found on seals.
p69
aVSo you see up there one such object.
p70
aVIt's the square object with the unicorn-like animal on it.
p71
aVNow that's a magnificent piece of art.
p72
aVSo how big do you think that is?
p73
aVPerhaps that big?
p74
aVOr maybe that big?
p75
aVWell let me show you.
p76
aVHere's a replica of one such seal.
p77
aVIt's only about one inch by one inch in size \u2014
p78
aVpretty tiny.
p79
aVSo what were these used for?
p80
aVWe know that these were used for stamping clay tags
p81
aVthat were attached to bundles of goods that were sent from one place to the other.
p82
aVSo you know those packing slips you get on your FedEx boxes?
p83
aVThese were used to make those kinds of packing slips.
p84
aVYou might wonder what these objects contain
p85
aVin terms of their text.
p86
aVPerhaps they're the name of the sender
p87
aVor some information about the goods
p88
aVthat are being sent from one place to the other \u2014 we don't know.
