aa(lp173
VThe first thing that you need to do when you have an undeciphered script
p174
aVis try to figure out the direction of writing.
p175
aVHere are two texts that contain some symbols on them.
p176
aVCan you tell me
p177
aVif the direction of writing is right to left or left to right?
p178
aVI'll give you a couple of seconds.
p179
aVOkay. Right to left, how many? Okay.
p180
aVOkay. Left to right?
p181
aVOh, it's almost 50/50. Okay.
p182
aVThe answer is:
p183
aVif you look at the left-hand side of the two texts,
p184
aVyou'll notice that there's a cramping of signs,
p185
aVand it seems like 4,000 years ago,
p186
aVwhen the scribe was writing from right to left,
p187
aVthey ran out of space.
p188
aVAnd so they had to cram the sign.
p189
aVOne of the signs is also below the text on the top.
p190
aVThis suggests the direction of writing
p191
aVwas probably from right to left,
p192
aVand so that's one of the first things we know,
p193
aVthat directionality is a very key aspect of linguistic scripts.
p194
aVAnd the Indus script now has
p195
aVthis particular property.
